{"parse":{"title":"Tertulia","pageid":1356949,"revid":858885562,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>tertulia</b> (<small>Spanish:&#160;</small><span title=\"Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\" class=\"IPA\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA/Spanish\" title=\"Help:IPA/Spanish\">[te\u027e\u02c8tulja]</a></span>; <small>Galician:&#160;</small><span title=\"Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\" class=\"IPA\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA/Galician\" title=\"Help:IPA/Galician\">[te\u027e\u02c8tulja]</a></span>; <a href=\"/wiki/Portuguese_language\" title=\"Portuguese language\">Portuguese</a>: <i><span lang=\"pt\">tert\u00falia</span></i> <small></small><span title=\"Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\" class=\"IPA\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA/Portuguese\" title=\"Help:IPA/Portuguese\">[t\u0268\u027e\u02c8tuli\u0250]</a></span>; <a href=\"/wiki/Catalan_language\" title=\"Catalan language\">Catalan</a>: <i><span lang=\"ca\">tert\u00falia</span></i> <small></small><span title=\"Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\" class=\"IPA\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA/Catalan\" title=\"Help:IPA/Catalan\">[t\u0259\u027e\u02c8tuli\u0259]</a></span>) is a social gathering with literary or artistic overtones, especially in <a href=\"/wiki/Iberian_Peninsula\" title=\"Iberian Peninsula\">Iberia</a> or in <a href=\"/wiki/Latin_America\" title=\"Latin America\">Latin America</a>. Tertulia also means an informal meeting of people to talk about current affairs, arts, etc. The word is originally <a href=\"/wiki/Spanish_language\" title=\"Spanish language\">Spanish</a> (borrowed by <a href=\"/wiki/Catalan_language\" title=\"Catalan language\">Catalan</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Portuguese_language\" title=\"Portuguese language\">Portuguese</a>), but it has only moderate currency in English, used mainly in describing Latin cultural contexts.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Format\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Format</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Etymology\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Etymology</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#In_the_Spanish_colonies\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">In the Spanish colonies</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Sources\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sources</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Format\">Format</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tertulia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Format\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>A tertulia is rather similar to a <a href=\"/wiki/Salon_(gathering)\" title=\"Salon (gathering)\">salon</a>, but a typical tertulia in recent centuries has been a regularly scheduled event in a public place such as a bar, although some tertulias are held in more private spaces, such as someone's living room. Participants, known as <i>contertulios</i>, may share their recent creations such as <a href=\"/wiki/Poetry\" title=\"Poetry\">poetry</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Short_stories\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Short stories\">short stories</a>, other writings, and even artwork or songs. Usually, but not always, the participants in a regularly scheduled tertulia are in some respects like-minded, with similar political or literary tastes.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (December 2017)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Etymology\">Etymology</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tertulia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Etymology\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Philip_II_of_Spain\" title=\"Philip II of Spain\">Philip II of Spain</a>, in the 16th century, was very interested in the ancient world and its cultures. Within his court, he employed <a href=\"/wiki/Polymath\" title=\"Polymath\">polymaths</a> such as <a href=\"/wiki/Juan_de_Mal_Lara\" title=\"Juan de Mal Lara\">Juan de Mal Lara</a> to compose poetry to accompany <a href=\"/wiki/Artwork\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Artwork\">artworks</a> which enriched his various palaces. Of great interest to the king were the works of the Christian author <a href=\"/wiki/Tertullian\" title=\"Tertullian\">Quintus Septimius Florens Tertullianus</a>. Courtiers and academics would gather to discuss such works with their royal patron, and so <i>tertulia</i> emerged as a term for learned discussion.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEtimolog\u00eda_de_Tertulia_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEtimolog\u00eda_de_Tertulia-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"In_the_Spanish_colonies\">In the Spanish colonies</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tertulia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: In the Spanish colonies\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>At <i>tertulias</i> before 1810 in at the houses of  <a href=\"/wiki/Buenos_Aires\" title=\"Buenos Aires\">Buenos Aires</a> society women such as <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mercedes_de_Lasalde_Riglos&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Mercedes de Lasalde Riglos (page does not exist)\">Mercedes de Lasalde Riglos</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Mariquita_S%C3%A1nchez_de_Thompson\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mariquita S\u00e1nchez de Thompson\">Mariquita S\u00e1nchez de Thompson</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Flora_Azcu%C3%A9naga\" title=\"Flora Azcu\u00e9naga\">Flora Azcu\u00e9naga</a> the discussions led up to the <a href=\"/wiki/May_Revolution\" title=\"May Revolution\">May Revolution</a>, the first stage in the struggle for Argentine independence from Spain.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllas_tambi\u00e9n_hicieron_el_25_de_Mayo_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllas_tambi\u00e9n_hicieron_el_25_de_Mayo-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n\"Madame Riglos\" could be seen as the chief lady of the Tory (conservative) faction in Buenos Aires.\nShe was sparkling and familiar, although highly aristocratic.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGalasso199435_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGalasso199435-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\nDo\u00f1a Melchora de Sarratea, queen of fashion and of the Buenos Aires salons, was so well aware of public and private affairs that she was held to be an enthusiastic supporter of Whig (liberal) principles.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGalasso199435_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGalasso199435-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\nMariquita S\u00e1nchez de Thompson's forte was foreign relations.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGalasso199436_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGalasso199436-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\nSimilar <i>tertulias</i> were being held during this period in <a href=\"/wiki/Lima\" title=\"Lima\">Lima</a>, Peru, by women such as Manuela R\u00e1bago de Avellafuertes de Riglos and Narcisa Arias de Saavaedra.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesBrewsterOwen200632_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesBrewsterOwen200632-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Antonio_Wilde\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"es:Jos\u00e9 Antonio Wilde\">Jos\u00e9 Antonio Wilde</a> (1813\u201387) described Buenos Aires in the period immediately following independence.\nHe wrote that it was a widespread custom among the more notable and well-to-do families, and also with many decent families, to give <i>tertulias</i> at least once a week.\nUsually the guests danced only from 8:00 to 12:00 at night, in which case only <a href=\"/wiki/Mate_(drink)\" title=\"Mate (drink)\">mate</a> was served, but if it went on later chocolate would be added.\nDress was not elaborate, and dancing, music and conversation were the only entertainment, so the cost was low.\nA piano player might be hired, or the young people might play dance pieces, or some old and complacent aunt might play some <a href=\"/wiki/Contradanza\" title=\"Contradanza\">contradanza</a>.\nEven if it was old, the thing was to dance.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWilde1908_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWilde1908-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tertulia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Pulqueria\" title=\"Pulqueria\">Pulqueria</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Stammtisch\" title=\"Stammtisch\">Stammtisch</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Tertullian\" title=\"Tertullian\">Tertullian</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Viennese_caf%C3%A9\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Viennese caf\u00e9\">Viennese caf\u00e9</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tertulia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEEtimolog\u00eda_de_Tertulia-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEtimolog\u00eda_de_Tertulia_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFEtimolog\u00eda_de_Tertulia\">Etimolog\u00eda de Tertulia</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllas_tambi\u00e9n_hicieron_el_25_de_Mayo-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllas_tambi\u00e9n_hicieron_el_25_de_Mayo_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFEllas_tambi\u00e9n_hicieron_el_25_de_Mayo\">Ellas tambi\u00e9n hicieron el 25 de Mayo</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEGalasso199435-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGalasso199435_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGalasso199435_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFGalasso1994\">Galasso 1994</a>, p.&#160;35.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEGalasso199436-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGalasso199436_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFGalasso1994\">Galasso 1994</a>, p.&#160;36.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesBrewsterOwen200632-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesBrewsterOwen200632_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFDaviesBrewsterOwen2006\">Davies, Brewster &amp; Owen 2006</a>, p.&#160;32.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEWilde1908-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWilde1908_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFWilde1908\">Wilde 1908</a>.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tertulia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r853264625\">.mw-parser-output .refbegin{font-size:90%;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul{list-style-type:none;margin-left:0}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul>li,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>dl>dd{margin-left:0;padding-left:3.2em;text-indent:-3.2em;list-style:none}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-100{font-size:100%}</style><div class=\"refbegin\" style=\"\">\n<ul><li><cite id=\"CITEREFDaviesBrewsterOwen2006\" class=\"citation\">Davies, Catherine; Brewster, Claire; Owen, Hilary (2006), <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=PtyD_4e8gVUC&amp;pg=PA32\"><i>South American Independence: Gender, Politics, Text</i></a>, Liverpool University Press, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-84631-027-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-84631-027-0\">978-1-84631-027-0</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">, retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2017-11-30</span></span></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=South+American+Independence%3A+Gender%2C+Politics%2C+Text&amp;rft.pub=Liverpool+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-84631-027-0&amp;rft.aulast=Davies&amp;rft.aufirst=Catherine&amp;rft.au=Brewster%2C+Claire&amp;rft.au=Owen%2C+Hilary&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DPtyD_4e8gVUC%26pg%3DPA32&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATertulia\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite id=\"CITEREFEllas_tambi\u00e9n_hicieron_el_25_de_Mayo\" class=\"citation\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://carteleradehistoria2.wordpress.com/2011/05/26/ellas-tambien-hicieron-el-25-de-mayo/#more-3234\">\"Ellas tambi\u00e9n hicieron el 25 de Mayo\"</a>, <i>Cartelera de Historia</i> (in Spanish), 26 May 2008<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">, retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2017-11-30</span></span></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Cartelera+de+Historia&amp;rft.atitle=Ellas+tambi%C3%A9n+hicieron+el+25+de+Mayo&amp;rft.date=2008-05-26&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fcarteleradehistoria2.wordpress.com%2F2011%2F05%2F26%2Fellas-tambien-hicieron-el-25-de-mayo%2F%23more-3234&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATertulia\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite id=\"CITEREFEtimolog\u00eda_de_Tertulia\" class=\"citation\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://etimologias.dechile.net/?tertulia\">\"Etimolog\u00eda de Tertulia\"</a>, <i>.dechile.net</i> (in Spanish)<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">, retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2017-12-02</span></span></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffm